### useCallback

`useCallback` returns a memoized version of a callback function that only changes when dependencies change. It prevents unnecessary re-renders of child components.

---

### Syntax

```jsx
import { useCallback } from 'react';

const memoizedCallback = useCallback(() => {
  doSomething(a, b);
}, [a, b]);
```

### Example with React.memo

```jsx
import { useCallback } from 'react';

function Parent() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
    console.log('Clicked');
  }, []);

  return (
    <>
      <ExpensiveButton onClick={handleClick} />
      <p>Count: {count}</p>
    </>
  );
}

const ExpensiveButton = React.memo(({ onClick }) => {
  console.log('Rendered');
  return <button onClick={onClick}>Click</button>;
});
```

### useCallback vs useMemo

| Hook | Returns | Use Case |
|------|---------|----------|
| `useCallback(fn, deps)` | The function itself | Memoizing callbacks passed to children |
| `useMemo(() => fn, deps)` | The returned value | Memoizing computation results |

### When to Use

- Passing callbacks to optimized child components with `React.memo`
- Functions in dependency arrays of other hooks
- Event handlers in components that re-render often

> **Key Point:** Do not use useCallback on every function. Premature optimization adds complexity. Use it when you have profiled and identified that a child component re-renders unnecessarily due to callback identity changes.

codeExample:
import { useCallback, useState } from 'react';

function SearchBar({ onSearch }) {
  const [query, setQuery] = useState('');

  const handleChange = useCallback((e) => {
    setQuery(e.target.value);
    onSearch(e.target.value);
  }, [onSearch]);

  return <input value={query} onChange={handleChange} />;
}
